// Section 04 — Self-NVC
#import "../utils.typ": divider, triple-star, section-heading, dropcap

#section-heading("IV", "Self-NVC")

#dropcap("M")[ost of the work of NVC happens before anyone hears anything come out of your mouth.]

There is a gap. Between when your friend says _I just don't think you respect me_ and the answer that finally leaves your face. Three seconds, usually. Sometimes the rest of the conversation. Sometimes the text sits on your phone for half an hour while your thumb hovers and you cycle through six versions of an answer. Sometimes the thing your boss said in the meeting becomes an email you write that night, after rewriting the second sentence four times. Most of the practice happens in those gaps — alone, with the version of you that gets loud when there is no one watching.

The first move is a pause. Not a long one. Long enough to ask:

_This is a feeling. What story am I telling myself about what just happened?_

One thing about the pause that's easy to miss: the inner monologue gets _louder_ and _faster_ when the body is dysregulated, not slower. The internal courtroom runs at full volume precisely when you are least equipped to translate anything. Self-NVC is only really available to a body that has decided, at least slightly, that it's safe enough to slow down. Feet on the floor. A few breaths. Something cold in your mouth. Walking out to the kitchen. The translation work happens in a body that has come back online — even partway. If the body is still spinning, the work is to come back online first. The words can wait.

#divider

Sometimes the feeling and the need are enough. The story underneath isn't always the homework.

Try this one. _I am feeling insecure tonight, and I am longing for some reassurance that you still find me attractive._

That sentence doesn't require a thirty-minute investigation of where the insecurity is from — your mother, your last relationship, the haircut, the lighting, the third glass of wine, the article about hormones, or all six at once. Sometimes the feeling is the feeling and the need is the need and the work is to say it. The historical research can wait, or happen later, or never happen at all. Right now, in your kitchen, what you have is enough.

This is, counter-intuitively, one of the harder moves to learn. Because the real trap, for many of us, isn't failing to find the story. The real trap is digging into the story when there was nothing in it that actually needed digging up.

*When the thinking is the avoidance.*

Thoughtful people, the readers of this kind of booklet most of all, run their own version of this trap. _Let me figure out why I am feeling this_ becomes the more sophisticated way of saying _let me not say what I am feeling._ The analysis works as a way to stay in the head and out of the body, out of the room, out of the request. Therapy and NVC and IFS and somatics and astrology and your friend's podcast all come pre-installed with permission to keep digging instead of speaking. The dig turns into the new performance.

The check is small. _Could I just say the feeling and the need now, here, to this person, and let the conversation happen from there?_ If yes, do that. The story can still be there afterward — it just doesn't have to be the first thing through the door.

#divider

*Talking to yourself differently.*

Most people, including you, conduct an ongoing internal conversation that, if spoken aloud to a child, would be recognized immediately as harm. _You are such an idiot. Why did you say that. Of course she didn't text back. You always do this. Look at you. Pull yourself together._ This is the standard internal soundtrack for a wide range of otherwise functional adults. Most of us can't remember a time when it wasn't running.

Self-NVC, practiced over time, slowly translates the language of that interior monologue into something else. The critic doesn't get silenced; it gets rendered in different grammar.

_You are such an idiot_ becomes _something in me is mortified, and I am longing for the thing not to have happened._

_Why did you say that_ becomes _I am embarrassed, and what I needed in that moment was to feel competent, and I did not._

_Pull yourself together_ becomes _something in me is exhausted, and I am longing for a few hours of not having to perform anything._

#triple-star

This isn't the positive-thinking move. Positive thinking installs a sentence that's untrue for the sake of feeling better. The voice here tells you what's actually happening in you, in precise language, in the tone you would use with someone you loved.

Given that voice consistently for long enough, something about the interior shifts. People who have been at this for a couple of decades report sounding different to themselves than they did at the start, without quite being able to point to the day it changed.

Sarah Peyton calls the part of you that learns to do this the _Resonating Self-Witness._ It is a part you are deliberately cultivating, in the same way one might cultivate a meditation practice or a dance form — slowly, by repetition, with no measurable progress on most days and a different person at the end of a year.

What it sounds like, lived from the inside, is not the absence of harshness. The harshness still shows up. Another voice is in the room when it does, already listening for it. After enough practice, the witness picks up the shift in the body before the inner critic finishes its sentence — sometimes before the critic has gotten its first word out. The chest tightens. Something starts to move toward _you idiot._ The witness gets there first: _something just got hot. What is it._ The translation begins before the attack does.

The harshness has somewhere to be received now. It doesn't run the room the way it used to.

*A word on the inner critic.*

The inner critic is one part of you among others. Usually a part that learned somewhere young that being harsh with yourself first was the only way to head off being harshly punished by someone else. The voice you have been mistaking for yourself is, on inspection, a frightened protector running a strategy that worked once. It's doing its best. It's wrong about what's currently required.

You don't have to fight it. You don't have to silence it. You can do the same translation move on it that you would do on anyone else. _Something in me is afraid. Something in me is trying to keep me safe by getting there first. What does that part actually need._ The internal monologue softens because the critic stops being the only voice in the room. Other voices — calmer, more accurate, usually quieter at first — start having space to speak.

#divider

*A note on Internal Family Systems.*

The two practices do different operations on the same internal moment. IFS works by helping the part that has been driving the bus step back from the wheel. NVC works by giving the part — once it has stepped back, or while it's still up there — a precise grammar to speak in. IFS asks _which part is this?_ NVC asks _what does this part actually feel, and what does it need?_

The two moves tend to amplify each other in practice. Once a part is no longer the whole self, you can locate what it actually feels and needs without being swept under by it. Once it has the grammar, it can be heard inside the system — not just noticed, but understood in its own terms by the rest of you. Either practice can address the same internal moment, and people who use both tend to stop noticing where the seam is.

Tuesday night. Your sister's text has been sitting on your phone for three days. Two parts of you have been at war about it. One wants to call her right now and have it out — get clarity, get this over with, get the not-knowing out of your body. The other wants to put the phone face-down and walk it off — give it another week, see if it gets less weird on its own.

Step one is to ask each part to step back far enough that you're not being swept under by either. Step two is to ask each one — separately — what it actually feels and what it actually needs.

The calling-now part, when it gets the floor: _I am furious. I need this to be over._

The walking-it-off part, when it gets the floor: _I am exhausted. I need this to be over._

Same longing, two costumes. Some older part of you has been waiting a long time for things with your sister to stop costing this much. The fight between the two parts was a fight about strategy — call now vs. wait it out — and the strategy fight had been running so loud that the actual want, which is just rest, never made it onto the table. Once it does, neither strategy has to win. Whoever writes back tomorrow is quieter than either of them.

You don't have to commit to either lineage to use the move. The small portable grammar of feelings and needs is most useful as a hinge between bigger traditions, not as a religion in its own right.

Feelings run their course; the interpretation shifts after. Often you don't need to know why. The feeling passes. The need, named, gets met or it doesn't. You move on.

Most often, when the pause has done its work and the feeling has been found, what's left is the need. _Connection. Rest. A say in your own life. Mattering. To be seen. Solitude. Care._

Speak from there. Or don't speak yet, because the speaking can come later, and right now what's needed is a breath, a walk, a bowl of soup, the second hour of sleep you had been refusing yourself.

Most of the practice never reaches anyone else's ears.
